---
import Layout from '../../components/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="FOIL templates">
  <article class="prose-measure mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold mb-2">FOIL templates</h1>
    <p class="text-stone-700">Three template letters for filing requests under the New York Freedom of Information Law (FOIL). Each is calm, procedural, and structured to get a written response on the record.</p>

    <div class="mt-8 space-y-3">
      <a href="/foil/policy-request/" class="block border border-stone-200 bg-white rounded p-4 no-underline hover:border-stone-400">
        <div class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold">1. District 1:1 device policy and contracts</div>
        <div class="text-sm text-stone-600 mt-1">Board policy, AUP, vendor contracts, take-home agreements.</div>
      </a>
      <a href="/foil/dpa-request/" class="block border border-stone-200 bg-white rounded p-4 no-underline hover:border-stone-400">
        <div class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold">2. Vendor data sharing agreements (DPAs)</div>
        <div class="text-sm text-stone-600 mt-1">Every DPA the district has signed, plus the Parents Bill of Rights for Data Privacy.</div>
      </a>
      <a href="/foil/compliance-request/" class="block border border-stone-200 bg-white rounded p-4 no-underline hover:border-stone-400">
        <div class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold">3. §2-d compliance documentation</div>
        <div class="text-sm text-stone-600 mt-1">Designated DPO, data inventory, breach log, parent complaints log.</div>
      </a>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-2">How FOIL works in NY</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 text-stone-700">
      <li><strong>Where to send it.</strong> Every NY school district must designate a Records Access Officer (RAO). The RAO is usually the district clerk; the contact is on the district website, often under "Board of Education," "FOIL," or "District Clerk."</li>
      <li><strong>Acknowledgment.</strong> The district must acknowledge your request within 5 business days.</li>
      <li><strong>Response.</strong> The district must produce records, deny the request, or specify a reasonable timeframe within 20 business days. Complex requests can take longer if the district justifies it in writing.</li>
      <li><strong>Appeal.</strong> A denial must be in writing and must explain the legal basis. You have 30 days to appeal in writing to the FOIL Appeals Officer (often the superintendent or board president).</li>
      <li><strong>Cost.</strong> The first 20¢/page (paper) or electronic delivery is typically free; large requests may incur copying fees, which the district must justify.</li>
      <li><strong>Form.</strong> Email is fine. Most districts have a form on their website; using the district's form when one exists usually speeds the response.</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="mt-6 text-sm text-stone-600">For the underlying statute, see the
      <a href="https://opengovernment.ny.gov/freedom-information-law">NY Committee on Open Government's FOIL guidance</a>.</p>

    <div class="disclaimer mt-8">
      Templates are starting points. For situations involving a denial or appeal, an education attorney can help.
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
